01:23:02,656 --> 01:23:07,150
Does he really think getting it one day
early is gonna give LSU a leg up?

1176
01:23:07,561 --> 01:23:10,359
Hey, have you filled all the slots
in the Army all-star game?

1177
01:23:10,531 --> 01:23:11,828
Yeah, why?

1178
01:23:11,999 --> 01:23:13,523
You might wanna open one up.

1179
01:23:20,340 --> 01:23:23,332
[PLAYERS YELLING
AND CROWD CHEERING OVER COMPUTER]

1180
01:23:30,517 --> 01:23:32,075
Oh.

1181
01:23:35,989 --> 01:23:37,013
Wow.

1182
01:23:37,791 --> 01:23:39,486
[LAUGHING]

1183
01:23:44,731 --> 01:23:46,892
[LAUGHING]

1184
01:23:52,272 --> 01:23:54,399
What did I tell you?

1185
01:24:03,217 --> 01:24:05,651
I want him. I want him bad.

1186
01:24:06,320 --> 01:24:11,053
<i>ALL: Y- E-L-L, everybody yell.
Say, everybody yell.</i>

1187
01:24:11,225 --> 01:24:15,093
<i>Y- E-L-L, everybody yell</i>

1188
01:24:15,262 --> 01:24:17,924
Nice kick this time, Collins. Nice job.

1189
01:24:18,098 --> 01:24:19,963
What in the world?

1190
01:24:20,267 --> 01:24:23,703
All right, y'all keep practicing.
Remember, point your toes.

1191
01:24:23,870 --> 01:24:28,864
<i>PLAYERS: One, two, three, one! One, two,
three, two! One, two, three, three!</i>

1192
01:24:29,042 --> 01:24:31,203
You gonna buckle up today, son?

1193
01:24:33,513 --> 01:24:36,880
Shoot, man, Fulmer's here.
Might as well go home.

1194
01:24:37,050 --> 01:24:40,178
What do you say, fellas? Doing
all right? Good to see everybody.

1195
01:24:40,354 --> 01:24:42,618
Came all the way from Knoxville
to see for myself.

1196
01:24:42,789 --> 01:24:45,917
Heck, coach, we drove from Clemson,
nine hours.

1197
01:24:46,093 --> 01:24:47,685
Coach Fulmer. It's a real honor.

1198
01:24:47,861 --> 01:24:50,796
My pleasure. I've watched your program.
You've done really well.

1199
01:24:50,964 --> 01:24:54,092
I don't think there's any question
you'll be at the next level soon.

1200
01:24:54,268 --> 01:24:57,101
Oh, well, you know, we do
what we can with what we've got.

1201
01:24:57,971 --> 01:25:00,565
Is that...? Is that Michael? Is that O'Hare?

1202
01:25:00,741 --> 01:25:05,007
It's Oher. Like a paddle in a boat. Oher.

1203
01:25:08,649 --> 01:25:11,550
You think we might see some drills,
perhaps?

1204
01:25:11,718 --> 01:25:15,779
- I think all the coaches would appreciate it.
- Oh, yes, sir. You bet.

1205
01:25:16,823 --> 01:25:17,847
[BLOWS WHISTLE]

1206
01:25:18,025 --> 01:25:19,890
Listen up, fellas!
We're gonna do a board drill.

1207
01:25:20,060 --> 01:25:22,551
Big Mike,
Jay Collis, best on best right here.

1208
01:25:22,729 --> 01:25:24,424
Let's go, come on, come on!

1209
01:25:24,598 --> 01:25:26,589
[PLAYERS YELLING]

1210
01:25:32,572 --> 01:25:33,664
On the whistle, men.

1211
01:25:46,186 --> 01:25:47,676
[BLOWS WHISTLE]

1212
01:25:47,854 --> 01:25:49,116
[GRUNTING]

1213
01:25:49,289 --> 01:25:50,984
[CROWD YELLING]

1214
01:25:54,127 --> 01:25:55,151
Wow.

1215
01:25:56,430 --> 01:25:59,422
[PHONES BEEP]

1216
01:26:02,202 --> 01:26:03,226
Coach. Thank you.

1217
01:26:03,403 --> 01:26:06,304
- Where are you off to, coach?
- Back to South Carolina.

1218
01:26:06,473 --> 01:26:10,534
You tell Michael Oher, if he can qualify
with the grades, Clemson wants him.

1219
01:26:10,711 --> 01:26:12,941
Yeah, good luck with that, Brad.

1220
01:26:13,113 --> 01:26:15,172
You've done a great job
with this young man.

1221
01:26:15,349 --> 01:26:17,544
He was a little raw
when we first got him...

1222
01:26:17,718 --> 01:26:20,152
...but we've, you know,
coached him up a little bit.

1223
01:26:23,256 --> 01:26:25,315
Where is that?

1224
01:26:25,492 --> 01:26:28,859
Well, make me guess.

1225
01:26:30,764 --> 01:26:31,788
Hello, Mama.

1226
01:26:31,965 --> 01:26:34,763
Did you know to be eligible
for a Division I scholarship...

1227
01:26:34,935 --> 01:26:39,031
...Michael will need to make a 2.5 GPA?
- Really?

1228
01:26:39,206 --> 01:26:43,734
His ACT is low and I don't see it getting
any better if he retakes it. Right there.

1229
01:26:43,910 --> 01:26:45,172
Well, what's his GPA now?

1230
01:26:45,345 --> 01:26:47,870
1.76.

1231
01:26:48,048 --> 01:26:50,312
That's not bad when you
consider where he started.

1232
01:26:50,484 --> 01:26:52,850
Well, he's gonna have to
make all A's this year.

1233
01:26:53,353 --> 01:26:56,948
I'm serious.
And that might not even be enough.

1234
01:26:57,124 --> 01:26:58,716
So he goes to a junior college.

1235
01:26:59,426 --> 01:27:02,327
Unh-uhn. Most inner-city kids that
go to JC drop out in the first year.

1236
01:27:02,496 --> 01:27:04,760
And his shot at the pros
would go out the window.

1237
01:27:04,931 --> 01:27:07,991
Pros? Are we even sure
he's gonna get college offers?

1238
01:27:11,171 --> 01:27:13,662
<i>NICK [OVER MACHINE]:
Michael, Nick Saban from LSU.</i>

1239
01:27:13,840 --> 01:27:16,206
<i>Looking forward to you
coming down and visiting.</i>

1240
01:27:16,376 --> 01:27:19,345
<i>LOU: Greetings, I'm Lou Holtz
from South Carolina. I'm call...</i>

1241
01:27:19,513 --> 01:27:23,005
<i>MAN: We are very interested in having
Michael over to Knoxville for a visit.</i>

1242
01:27:24,251 --> 01:27:25,479
Phil Fulmer, Tennessee.

1243
01:27:25,652 --> 01:27:30,055
There's 20 more of them on there.
And these things right here, 50 of them.

1244
01:27:30,223 --> 01:27:31,690
- Any of those from Ole Miss?
- No.

1245
01:27:31,858 --> 01:27:34,793
They're not gonna start recruiting
till they hire another coach.

1246
01:27:34,961 --> 01:27:38,692
Doesn't make any difference
unless Michael makes his grades. Ahem.

1247
01:27:40,066 --> 01:27:41,090
What are we gonna do?

1248
01:27:43,244 --> 01:27:46,338
I understand you applied
for a teaching position at Wingate.

1249
01:27:47,581 --> 01:27:49,378
I wasn't religious enough for them.

1250
01:27:50,017 --> 01:27:55,580
I'm a spiritual person, Mrs. Tuohy,
but I have certain, shall we say, doubts.

1251
01:27:56,657 --> 01:27:58,682
Well, I appreciate your honesty,
Miss Sue.

1252
01:27:59,059 --> 01:28:00,651
What's the situation with Michael?

1253
01:28:00,828 --> 01:28:03,296
- He needs to do better in school.
- Obviously.

1254
01:28:03,464 --> 01:28:04,726
But why the big push?

1255
01:28:04,898 --> 01:28:08,959
Well, he's in line for a football
scholarship if he gets his grades up.

1256
01:28:09,136 --> 01:28:12,299
- Is he considering Ole Miss?
- Better be.

1257
01:28:13,707 --> 01:28:15,265
I'd love to work with him.

1258
01:28:15,442 --> 01:28:17,842
Well, when would you like to start?

1259
01:28:18,712 --> 01:28:22,580
Mrs. Tuohy, um, there's something
you should know about me.

1260
01:28:22,750 --> 01:28:24,445
I don't usually tell many people...

1261
01:28:24,618 --> 01:28:28,281
...but it's something I feel you should
be aware of before you hire me.

1262
01:28:28,956 --> 01:28:31,015
Uh... What is it?

1263
01:28:31,925 --> 01:28:33,449
I'm a Democrat.

1264
01:28:35,596 --> 01:28:37,359
Okay.

1265
01:28:42,636 --> 01:28:45,161
- I don't understand it.
- Yet.

1266
01:28:45,339 --> 01:28:47,603
You don't understand it yet.

1267
01:28:49,410 --> 01:28:50,900
How big is your head, Michael?

1268
01:28:51,145 --> 01:28:52,476
Big.

1269
01:28:52,646 --> 01:28:54,079
And what's in there?

1270
01:28:54,248 --> 01:28:55,545
- A brain.
- A brain.

1271
01:28:55,716 --> 01:28:57,411
It's full of knowledge.

1272
01:28:57,584 --> 01:29:02,214
Like a file cabinet with maps,
and shortcuts for figuring things out.

1273
01:29:02,890 --> 01:29:06,724
You'll get there, Michael Oher, because
I'm here to help you use those maps...

1274
01:29:06,894 --> 01:29:10,921
...and reach your destination,
like Sacagawea led Lewis and Clark.

1275
01:29:11,098 --> 01:29:12,326
Sacagawea?

1276
01:29:12,499 --> 01:29:15,866
We'll get to that.
And the history books have it wrong.

1277
01:29:16,036 --> 01:29:19,233
All you need to know
is I'll get you there.

1278
01:29:20,040 --> 01:29:22,031
Do you believe me?

1279
01:29:24,812 --> 01:29:26,439
You trust me, Michael?

1280
01:29:28,682 --> 01:29:29,706
Yes, Miss Sue.

1281
01:29:32,553 --> 01:29:33,747
Try it again.

1282
01:29:35,289 --> 01:29:38,122
What's the next one? Read that
to me. Okay, what does it say?

1283
01:29:38,292 --> 01:29:42,729
First we have to find the constant.
Now, where is the constant?

1284
01:29:43,330 --> 01:29:45,491
Good. See?

1285
01:29:45,666 --> 01:29:48,863
Who'd have thought we'd have
a black son before we knew a Democrat?

1286
01:29:49,036 --> 01:29:50,594
[DOORBELL RINGS]

1287
01:29:51,038 --> 01:29:54,235
LEIGH ANNE: Doorbell!
SEAN: I got it, guys.

1288
01:29:56,844 --> 01:29:58,903
Coach, how are you? Come in.
Sean Tuohy.

1289
01:29:59,079 --> 01:30:01,877
- Nick Saban, nice to meet you.
- Nice to see you. My pleasure.

1290
01:30:02,049 --> 01:30:04,313
I appreciate the opportunity
to come in your home.

1291
01:30:04,485 --> 01:30:06,919
- This is my daughter, Collins.
- Pleasure to meet you.

1292
01:30:07,087 --> 01:30:09,954
- And you must be Leigh Anne.
- That would be me, Coach Saban.

1293
01:30:10,124 --> 01:30:11,557
- Nice to meet you.
- You too.

1294
01:30:11,725 --> 01:30:14,216
Just call me Nick.
This is an incredible home.

1295
01:30:14,395 --> 01:30:16,625
The Windsor valances are a nice touch.

1296
01:30:16,797 --> 01:30:20,790
Well, thank you.
You obviously have excellent taste.

1297
01:30:20,968 --> 01:30:22,902
NICK:
Well, we appreciate quality...

1298
01:30:23,070 --> 01:30:24,935
...and recognize it when we see it.

1299
01:30:26,507 --> 01:30:28,907
Michael, why don't you come in
and say hello?

1300
01:30:29,076 --> 01:30:31,408
- Nick Saban. Nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

1301
01:30:31,578 --> 01:30:33,671
NICK: And you must be SJ.
- That's me.

1302
01:30:33,847 --> 01:30:37,248
Michael, why don't you and Nick
go into the living room and talk?

1303
01:30:37,584 --> 01:30:38,710
Can SJ come?

1304
01:30:38,886 --> 01:30:41,912
- Absolutely. We'll recruit the both of you.
- All right.

1305
01:30:44,925 --> 01:30:47,086
I find him extremely handsome.

1306
01:30:47,261 --> 01:30:49,161
Yeah, I'm right here, Leigh Anne.

1307
01:30:49,329 --> 01:30:50,853
Yeah, I know.

1308
01:30:51,031 --> 01:30:54,023
NICK: So, Michael, we would love
to get you down to LSU for a visit.

1309
01:30:54,201 --> 01:30:56,169
We've got a great thing going
right now.

1310
01:30:56,336 --> 01:30:59,794
You have an opportunity to be
successful as a person, as a student...

1311
01:30:59,973 --> 01:31:04,205
...and an opportunity to be a part of the
next national championship team at LSU.

1312
01:31:04,378 --> 01:31:07,404
So, what do you say?
Would you like to commit to a visit?

1313
01:31:07,581 --> 01:31:09,014
SJ: Can I ask a question?
NICK: Sure.

1314
01:31:09,349 --> 01:31:12,876
My brother and I are very close,
and so...

1315
01:31:13,053 --> 01:31:17,888
...I'm very afraid that if he goes off
to school, I might not get to see him.

1316
01:31:18,058 --> 01:31:19,719
- So...
- Go on.

1317
01:31:19,893 --> 01:31:23,693
I guess I was just wondering
how much access I'd have to him.

1318
01:31:23,864 --> 01:31:26,298
NICK: Well, SJ, you would have
total access to Michael.

1319
01:31:26,467 --> 01:31:29,561
But better than that, in his first game
in Tiger Stadium...

1320
01:31:29,736 --> 01:31:32,500
...we would like for you to lead
the team out of the tunnel.

1321
01:31:32,673 --> 01:31:35,073
- What do you think about that?
- Sounds good.

1322
01:31:37,678 --> 01:31:39,669
[CROWD CHEERING]

1323
01:31:42,649 --> 01:31:44,640
[GRUNTING]

1324
01:31:46,653 --> 01:31:48,587
[DOORBELL RINGS]

1325
01:31:49,556 --> 01:31:50,750
Come on in.

1326
01:31:50,924 --> 01:31:54,121
Greetings. I'm Lou Holtz from
the University of South Carolina.

1327
01:31:54,294 --> 01:31:57,263
Leigh Anne Tuohy. Nice to meet you.
Come on in. Michael?

1328
01:31:57,431 --> 01:31:59,558
Hello. I'm Tommy Tuberville,
Auburn University.

1329
01:31:59,733 --> 01:32:01,928
Leigh Anne Tuohy. Nice to meet you.
Michael?

1330
01:32:02,102 --> 01:32:05,560
- Houston Nutt, University of Arkansas.
- Leigh Anne Tuohy. Nice to meet you.

1331
01:32:05,739 --> 01:32:08,264
- Ole Miss cup, huh?
- Michael?

1332
01:32:09,243 --> 01:32:10,267
[SIGHS]

1333
01:32:10,444 --> 01:32:12,708
Oh, come on. You know this.

1334
01:32:12,880 --> 01:32:14,609
It's logical.

1335
01:32:25,859 --> 01:32:28,419
I guarantee, you come to
University of South Carolina...

1336
01:32:28,595 --> 01:32:31,086
...it'll be the smartest decision
you've ever made.

1337
01:32:31,265 --> 01:32:34,894
We want you, we need you,
but the other thing is, Mike, you need us.

1338
01:32:38,639 --> 01:32:39,663
Ow!

1339
01:32:39,840 --> 01:32:42,775
Knoxville is a tremendous place
to live and...

1340
01:32:42,943 --> 01:32:45,935
HOUSTON: I know there's Lions,
there's Tigers, there's Bears.

1341
01:32:46,113 --> 01:32:48,240
Hey, there's only one Razorback
in the world.

1342
01:32:48,415 --> 01:32:52,146
And not only that, you will look great
in Gamecock red.

1343
01:32:52,319 --> 01:32:53,343
What's in it for me?

1344
01:32:53,520 --> 01:32:57,217
SJ, I'm gonna get you a hog hat
and the whole family a hog hat.

1345
01:32:57,391 --> 01:32:59,518
Are you telling me that's
the best you can do?

1346
01:32:59,693 --> 01:33:01,991
SJ, you remind me of me as a boy.

1347
01:33:02,162 --> 01:33:04,528
Coach, help me help you.

1348
01:33:04,698 --> 01:33:08,225
I can give you a Gamecock headdress,
and with real feathers.

1349
01:33:17,010 --> 01:33:20,411
- What do you got for me, Phil?
- I've been thinking a lot about that...

1350
01:33:20,581 --> 01:33:23,175
...and one of the things
I think would be special...

1351
01:33:23,350 --> 01:33:27,343
...is we'll walk arm-in-arm to the center
of Neyland Stadium in the first ball game...

1352
01:33:27,521 --> 01:33:29,853
...and do the coin toss together.
How's that sound?

1353
01:33:30,023 --> 01:33:32,491
Coach Fulmer, it's a pleasure
doing business with you.

1354
01:33:32,659 --> 01:33:35,457
My pleasure, CJ. You bet you, buddy.

1355
01:33:35,629 --> 01:33:37,597
[CROWD CHEERING]

1356
01:33:44,004 --> 01:33:45,028
[DOORBELL RINGS]

1357
01:33:45,772 --> 01:33:47,296
Congratulations on getting hired.

1358
01:33:47,474 --> 01:33:50,238
Thank you, ma'am.
Ole Miss is my dream job.

1359
01:33:50,410 --> 01:33:53,538
You're coming a little late to the party
and we're diehard Rebels...

1360
01:33:53,714 --> 01:33:56,148
...so I'm gonna pretty much
give you a road map.

1361
01:33:56,316 --> 01:33:57,943
- Got it.
- LSU is out.

1362
01:33:58,118 --> 01:34:00,109
Everybody knows Saban's
going to the NFL.

1363
01:34:00,287 --> 01:34:03,085
Don't wanna name names,
but on Michael's first two trips...

1364
01:34:03,256 --> 01:34:05,520
...somebody took him to a titty bar.
- Terrible.

1365
01:34:05,692 --> 01:34:07,887
Tell me about it.
He had nightmares for weeks.

1366
01:34:08,061 --> 01:34:10,359
So when he visits,
I want you to feed him Italian.

1367
01:34:10,530 --> 01:34:13,124
He likes fettuccine Alfredo.
And take him to a movie.

1368
01:34:13,300 --> 01:34:16,531
<i>Not Chainsaw Massacre
because he'll just cover his eyes.</i>

1369
01:34:16,703 --> 01:34:19,103
Then get him in bed by 10. Got it?

1370
01:34:19,272 --> 01:34:20,466
- Yes, ma'am.
- All right.

1371
01:34:20,641 --> 01:34:22,472
- What about Tennessee?
- Mm.

1372
01:34:22,809 --> 01:34:24,640
Breaks my heart,
but they're still in the hunt.

1373
01:34:24,811 --> 01:34:27,177
Ahem. Fulmer made SJ a sweet deal.

1374
01:34:27,347 --> 01:34:29,907
- I hear that kid can really pepper the gumbo.
- Hmm.

1375
01:34:30,083 --> 01:34:32,813
He's his daddy's boy. You ready?

1376
01:34:32,986 --> 01:34:34,886
- Let's do it.
- All right.

1377
01:34:35,055 --> 01:34:37,489
ED: Mike, do you love barbecue?
I tell you what, Mike.

1378
01:34:37,658 --> 01:34:41,116
You can go to a gas station and
get the best barbecue you ever got.

1379
01:34:41,294 --> 01:34:42,761
It's a wonderful place to live.

1380
01:34:42,929 --> 01:34:47,093
Fried catfish, all the good food that
we love to eat and that's not good for us...

1381
01:34:47,267 --> 01:34:49,531
...you can have it there, Mike,
I promise you.

1382
01:34:49,703 --> 01:34:52,001
And for you, SJ, this is what I can do.

1383
01:34:52,172 --> 01:34:54,265
At Ole Miss, we have
The Grove by the stadium.

1384
01:34:54,441 --> 01:34:57,842
We walk it before every game
in front of thousands of people.

1385
01:34:58,011 --> 01:34:59,911
It's a sacred ritual. And I'm in front.

1386
01:35:00,447 --> 01:35:02,347
Seen it a thousand times.

1387
01:35:02,516 --> 01:35:06,282
Ever seen it from the front of the line?
Next year, you and me, leading the team.

1388
01:35:06,453 --> 01:35:10,389
Tennessee offered to let me
run on the field and flip the coin.

1389
01:35:13,326 --> 01:35:15,385
I'll throw in a sideline pass.

1390
01:35:25,672 --> 01:35:27,105
Have you decided yet, Michael?

1391
01:35:27,874 --> 01:35:29,774
No, Miss Sue.

1392
01:35:30,544 --> 01:35:32,910
But you like Tennessee?

1393
01:35:33,880 --> 01:35:35,211
Yeah. That's a good school.

1394
01:35:36,316 --> 01:35:38,307
Not at the academic level of Ole Miss...

1395
01:35:38,485 --> 01:35:41,477
...but they have a outstanding
Science Department.

1396
01:35:42,355 --> 01:35:44,585
You know what they're famous for?

1397
01:35:45,025 --> 01:35:47,289
They work with the FBI...

1398
01:35:47,461 --> 01:35:51,420
...to study the effects of soil
on decomposing body parts.

1399
01:35:51,598 --> 01:35:53,293
What's that mean?

1400
01:35:53,467 --> 01:35:56,925
Well, when they find a body, the police
wanna know how long it's been dead.

1401
01:35:57,104 --> 01:36:00,039
So the fine folks at Tennessee
help them out.

1402
01:36:00,841 --> 01:36:03,537
Oh, they have lots of body parts.

1403
01:36:03,744 --> 01:36:07,805
Arms and legs and hands...

1404
01:36:07,981 --> 01:36:10,506
...from hospitals and medical schools.

1405
01:36:11,084 --> 01:36:12,381
[CHUCKLES]

1406
01:36:13,286 --> 01:36:15,151
And do you know where they store them?

1407
01:36:19,092 --> 01:36:21,253
Right underneath the football field.

1408
01:36:23,430 --> 01:36:27,958
So while it's fine and dandy
to have 100,000 fans cheering for you...

1409
01:36:28,135 --> 01:36:32,765
...the bodies you should be worried about
are the ones right under the turf.

1410
01:36:32,939 --> 01:36:36,033
Set to poke up through the ground
and grab you.

1411
01:36:40,847 --> 01:36:43,816
Well, it's your decision
where you wanna play ball.

1412
01:36:43,984 --> 01:36:46,179
Don't let me influence you.

1413
01:36:55,962 --> 01:36:57,395
[APPLAUSE]

1414
01:37:14,848 --> 01:37:18,113
All the other teachers are on board.
I don't know what your problem is.

1415
01:37:18,285 --> 01:37:22,221
I'm sorry. I will not give a student
a grade he or she doesn't deserve.

1416
01:37:22,522 --> 01:37:25,855
Well, Michael needs a B.

1417
01:37:26,026 --> 01:37:28,688
What does he have to do
to deserve that?

1418
01:37:30,363 --> 01:37:33,230
Right now Michael's doing
C-minus, D-plus work.

1419
01:37:33,800 --> 01:37:37,566
His best chance at improvement is
the written essay at the end of the year.

1420
01:37:37,737 --> 01:37:39,830
It counts for a third of the grade.

1421
01:37:41,208 --> 01:37:43,870
Well, that's it. We're sunk.

1422
01:37:44,044 --> 01:37:45,068
[GAME PLAYING ON TV]

1423
01:37:45,245 --> 01:37:48,112
<i>Why don't you write about
Great Expectations?</i>

1424
01:37:48,281 --> 01:37:50,146
You're a lot like Pip.

1425
01:37:50,317 --> 01:37:55,778
I mean, he was poor. He was an orphan
and someone kind of found him.

1426
01:37:55,956 --> 01:37:57,856
You should be able to relate to that.

1427
01:38:01,928 --> 01:38:04,988
Fine. We'll go through the reading list.

1428
01:38:05,165 --> 01:38:07,861
But you're gonna have to pick one,
Michael.

1429
01:38:08,301 --> 01:38:09,325
<i>Pygmalion.</i>

1430
01:38:12,772 --> 01:38:14,603
<i>A Tale of Two Cities.</i>

1431
01:38:14,774 --> 01:38:16,639
"The Charge of the Light Brigade."

1432
01:38:16,810 --> 01:38:20,246
<i>Half a league, half a league
Half a league onward</i>

1433
01:38:20,413 --> 01:38:21,971
I love that one.

1434
01:38:22,349 --> 01:38:24,613
He loves it.

1435
01:38:26,286 --> 01:38:29,744
Why don't you do this?
And I'll watch basketball.

1436
01:38:33,493 --> 01:38:34,892
SEAN:
Okay.

1437
01:38:38,498 --> 01:38:42,127
<i>All in the valley of Death
Rode the six hundred.</i>

1438
01:38:42,969 --> 01:38:46,928
They named LSU's stadium Death Valley
because of this story.

1439
01:38:48,008 --> 01:38:51,569
Alfred, Lord Tennyson
was writing about LSU-Ole Miss.

1440
01:38:51,745 --> 01:38:53,076
- You're kidding.
- No.

1441
01:38:53,246 --> 01:38:56,340
- It's a great story.
- It's a poem!

1442
01:38:56,516 --> 01:38:58,984
<i>"Forward, the Light Brigade!"</i>

1443
01:38:59,152 --> 01:39:00,483
That's like the offense.

1444
01:39:00,654 --> 01:39:02,781
<i>"Charge for the guns," he said:</i>

1445
01:39:02,956 --> 01:39:04,150
It's the end zone.

1446
01:39:04,691 --> 01:39:07,091
<i>Into the valley of Death
Rode the six hundred.</i>

1447
01:39:07,260 --> 01:39:10,991
<i>"Forward, the Light Brigade!"
Was there a man dismay'd?</i>

1448
01:39:11,731 --> 01:39:15,064
<i>Not tho' the soldier knew
Someone had blunder'd:</i>

1449
01:39:15,235 --> 01:39:16,759
Someone made a mistake?

1450
01:39:17,337 --> 01:39:19,805
Yeah. Their leader.

1451
01:39:20,106 --> 01:39:21,334
Their coach.

1452
01:39:23,310 --> 01:39:27,440
But why would they go ahead
if they knew he messed up?

1453
01:39:30,083 --> 01:39:32,517
<i>Theirs not to make reply</i>

1454
01:39:32,852 --> 01:39:35,548
<i>Theirs not to reason why</i>

1455
01:39:35,922 --> 01:39:38,356
<i>Theirs but to do and die:</i>

1456
01:39:39,092 --> 01:39:42,061
<i>Into the valley of Death
Rode the six hundred.</i>

1457
01:39:44,864 --> 01:39:46,559
They're all gonna die, aren't they?

1458
01:39:48,868 --> 01:39:49,892
Yeah.

1459
01:39:53,440 --> 01:39:56,136
That's really, really sad.

1460
01:39:59,312 --> 01:40:02,145
I think you just found
something to write about, Michael.

1461
01:40:18,531 --> 01:40:20,999
<i>MICHAEL:
Courage is a hard thing to figure.</i>

1462
01:40:21,167 --> 01:40:25,035
<i>You can have courage based
on a dumb idea or a mistake...</i>

1463
01:40:25,205 --> 01:40:27,503
<i>... but you're not supposed to
question adults...</i>

1464
01:40:27,674 --> 01:40:31,906
<i>... or your coach or your teacher
because they make the rules.</i>

1465
01:40:32,879 --> 01:40:36,576
<i>Maybe they know best,
but maybe they don't.</i>

1466
01:40:37,650 --> 01:40:41,677
<i>It all depends on who you are,
where you come from.</i>

1467
01:40:41,855 --> 01:40:44,722
<i>Didn't at least one of the 600 guys
think about giving up...</i>

1468
01:40:44,891 --> 01:40:47,121
<i>... and joining with the other side?</i>

1469
01:40:47,293 --> 01:40:51,127
<i>I mean, valley of Death,
that's pretty salty stuff.</i>

1470
01:40:53,566 --> 01:40:55,363
<i>That's why courage is tricky.</i>

1471
01:40:56,403 --> 01:40:59,770
<i>Should you always do
what others tell you to do?</i>

1472
01:41:00,407 --> 01:41:03,570
<i>Sometimes you might not even know
why you're doing something.</i>

1473
01:41:03,743 --> 01:41:06,439
<i>I mean, any fool can have courage.</i>

1474
01:41:07,247 --> 01:41:11,240
<i>But honor, that's the real reason
you either do something or you don't.</i>

1475
01:41:11,818 --> 01:41:14,753
<i>It's who you are
and maybe who you want to be.</i>

1476
01:41:16,156 --> 01:41:18,317
<i>If you die trying for
something important...</i>

1477
01:41:18,491 --> 01:41:22,951
<i>... then you have both honor and
courage, and that's pretty good.</i>

1478
01:41:23,530 --> 01:41:25,828
<i>I think that's what the writer was saying.</i>

1479
01:41:25,999 --> 01:41:29,833
<i>That you should hope for courage
and try for honor.</i>

1480
01:41:30,003 --> 01:41:35,566
<i>And maybe even pray that the people
telling you what to do have some too.</i>

1481
01:41:39,612 --> 01:41:41,273
Kevin Lin.

1482
01:41:41,448 --> 01:41:43,439
[APPLAUSE]

1483
01:41:46,319 --> 01:41:49,220
- Good job.
- Excuse me. Excuse me. Excuse me.

1484
01:41:50,557 --> 01:41:53,492
Matthew Nichols.

1485
01:41:54,160 --> 01:41:57,095
- 2.52.
- Hmm?

1486
01:41:57,297 --> 01:42:01,529
Michael's final GPA.
Got it off of Paul's computer.

1487
01:42:01,734 --> 01:42:03,793
He did it, Sean. He did it.

1488
01:42:04,504 --> 01:42:06,802
Wait a minute. You broke into
the principal's computer?

1489
01:42:06,973 --> 01:42:08,440
Hmm?

1490
01:42:09,509 --> 01:42:11,272
Michael Oher.

1491
01:42:11,444 --> 01:42:13,309
[APPLAUSE]

1492
01:42:13,480 --> 01:42:14,504
[CHUCKLES]

1493
01:42:15,582 --> 01:42:17,413
GIRL:
Michael.

1494
01:42:18,318 --> 01:42:21,014
Where in the world did you find
a baby picture of Michael?

1495
01:42:21,187 --> 01:42:24,122
